&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;For food colouring&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Baking soda &lt;/strong&gt;is primarily used in cooking as a &lt;strong&gt;leavening agent&lt;/strong&gt;, helping baked goods rise by releasing carbon dioxide gas when combined with acidic ingredients.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is a common ingredient in &lt;strong&gt;antacids&lt;/strong&gt;, which help neutralize stomach acid and relieve heartburn or indigestion.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Baking soda is utilized in &lt;strong&gt;fire extinguishers&lt;/strong&gt;, especially for kitchen fires, as it releases carbon dioxide to smother flames.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Baking soda &lt;strong&gt;does not serve as a food coloring agent&lt;/strong&gt;; its chemical properties are not designed for altering the color of food.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Its versatility makes it useful for cooking, cleaning, and even personal care, but food coloring is not one of its applications.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Leavening Agent:&lt;/strong&gt; Baking soda (sodium bicarbonate) reacts with acidic substances like vinegar or lemon juice to produce carbon dioxide, which causes dough or batter to expand and rise.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Antacid Properties:&lt;/strong&gt; As a mild alkaline substance, baking soda neutralizes excess stomach acid, providing relief for conditions like heartburn and acid reflux.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Fire Extinguishing Use:&lt;/strong&gt; Baking soda releases carbon dioxide when heated, which helps extinguish small grease fires by cutting off the oxygen supply.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Other Household Uses:&lt;/strong&gt; Baking soda is widely used for cleaning, deodorizing, and personal care, such as teeth whitening and skin exfoliation.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Food Coloring Agents:&lt;/strong&gt; Food coloring involves dyes or pigments specifically designed to alter the color of food, unlike baking soda, which has no such chemical properties.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&lt;strong&gt; &lt;u&gt;Lactic acid and energy.&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Cellular respiration is a breakdown of a complex molecule into simpler forms and also results in the release of energy.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the presence of oxygen aerobic respiration occurs.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the absence of oxygen anaerobic respiration occurs.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Anaerobic respiration in our body muscles produces Lactic acid and energy.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;In the absence of oxygen, pyruvate is converted to form lactic acid, and energy is released.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;It leads to muscle cramps and pain.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Oxygen and water:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is &lt;strong&gt;released during complete oxidation in a citric acid cycle.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It occurs inside the mitochondrial matrix.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Formic acid and energy:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is produced by ants.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It acts as a&lt;strong&gt; hydrogen energy carrier.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Alcohol:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It&lt;strong&gt; is produced during fermentation reactions.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Methanol and ethanol are examples.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Wien&amp;#39;s Displacement Law&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Wien&amp;#39;s Displacement Law&lt;/strong&gt; explains the relationship between the temperature of a black body and the wavelength at which it emits radiation most strongly.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It states that the wavelength corresponding to the peak emission of radiation is inversely proportional to the temperature of the black body. &lt;strong&gt;Mathematically, &amp;lambda;_max = b/T&lt;/strong&gt;, where &lt;strong&gt;&amp;lambda;_max&lt;/strong&gt; is the peak wavelength, &lt;strong&gt;T&lt;/strong&gt; is the temperature, and &lt;strong&gt;b&lt;/strong&gt; is Wien&amp;#39;s constant (approximately &lt;strong&gt;2.897 &amp;times; 10⁻&amp;sup3; m&amp;middot;K&lt;/strong&gt;).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This law helps us understand the colors emitted by black bodies like stars, including the &lt;strong&gt;Sun&lt;/strong&gt;, based on their surface temperature. For example, hotter stars emit blue light, while cooler stars emit red light.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The law was formulated by &lt;strong&gt;Wilhelm Wien&lt;/strong&gt; in &lt;strong&gt;1893&lt;/strong&gt; and is a fundamental concept in &lt;strong&gt;thermodynamics and astrophysics&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is widely applied in determining the temperature of celestial objects by analyzing the spectrum of their emitted radiation.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hooke&amp;#39;s Law:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Hooke&amp;#39;s Law pertains to the &lt;strong&gt;elasticity of materials&lt;/strong&gt; and states that the force needed to extend or compress a spring is proportional to the distance it is stretched or compressed (&lt;strong&gt;F = kx&lt;/strong&gt;, where &lt;strong&gt;k&lt;/strong&gt; is the spring constant).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is unrelated to black body radiation or temperature.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Snell&amp;#39;s Law:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Snell&amp;#39;s Law describes the &lt;strong&gt;refraction of light&lt;/strong&gt; as it passes from one medium to another, stating that the ratio of the sine of the angles of incidence and refraction is proportional to the refractive indices of the media (&lt;strong&gt;n₁ sin &amp;theta;₁ = n₂ sin &amp;theta;₂&lt;/strong&gt;).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This law is used in optics and is not related to the emission of radiation by black bodies.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Kepler&amp;#39;s Laws of Planetary Motion:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;These laws describe the motion of planets around the Sun:&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1st Law:&lt;/strong&gt; Planets move in elliptical orbits with the Sun at one focus.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;2nd Law:&lt;/strong&gt; A line segment joining a planet and the Sun sweeps out equal areas during equal intervals of time.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;3rd Law:&lt;/strong&gt; The square of the orbital period of a planet is proportional to the cube of the semi-major axis of its orbit.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;While these laws are significant in celestial mechanics, they do not explain the colors of black bodies based on their temperature.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Important Points:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Wien&amp;#39;s Displacement Law&lt;/strong&gt; is essential for understanding the spectrum of stars and other celestial objects, allowing scientists to estimate their &lt;strong&gt;surface temperatures&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The Sun, for example, emits radiation most strongly at a wavelength of approximately &lt;strong&gt;500 nm&lt;/strong&gt; (green light), corresponding to its surface temperature of about &lt;strong&gt;5778 K&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is a crucial tool in &lt;strong&gt;astrophysics&lt;/strong&gt; and helps in the study of &lt;strong&gt;stellar evolution&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p data-end=&quot;57&quot; data-start=&quot;0&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;3.62%&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p data-end=&quot;57&quot; data-start=&quot;0&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;284&quot; data-start=&quot;78&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Sodium hypochlorite&lt;/strong&gt; is the active ingredient in most commercial bleaching solutions.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;605&quot; data-start=&quot;482&quot;&gt;It is typically present in a concentration of &lt;strong&gt;3.62%&lt;/strong&gt; in commercial bleach formulations, which makes it effective for cleaning, disinfecting, and whitening.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;692&quot; data-start=&quot;610&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Mass percentage&lt;/strong&gt; refers to the amount of a specific compound in a mixture expressed as a percentage of the total mass. In this case, the mass percentage of sodium hypochlorite is calculated based on its concentration in the solution.&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;Hence, the correct concentration is 3.62%.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;1041&quot; data-start=&quot;850&quot;&gt;Other options such as &lt;strong&gt;0.0546&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;0.0257&lt;/strong&gt;, and &lt;strong&gt;0.1085&lt;/strong&gt; are incorrect as they are not representative of the typical concentration of sodium hypochlorite in commercial bleaching solutions. These values might refer to other formulations or diluted solutions.&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;Hence, these options are incorrect.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;1162&quot; data-start=&quot;1046&quot;&gt;Commercial bleach is designed to provide a balance between cleaning efficacy and safety, and the &lt;strong&gt;3.62%&lt;/strong&gt; concentration is ideal for household purposes.&amp;nbsp;&lt;em style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;Hence, 3.62% is the correct answer.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Sodium Hypochlorite:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;2410&quot; data-start=&quot;2195&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Sodium hypochlorite&lt;/strong&gt; is a chemical compound with the formula &lt;strong&gt;NaOCl&lt;/strong&gt;. It is widely used as a bleaching agent and disinfectant in household and industrial applications.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;2684&quot; data-start=&quot;2415&quot;&gt;It is commonly found in &lt;strong&gt;liquid bleach&lt;/strong&gt; and is known for its ability to remove stains, disinfect surfaces, and whiten fabrics.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Concentration in Commercial Bleach:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;2860&quot; data-start=&quot;2735&quot;&gt;The typical concentration of &lt;strong&gt;sodium hypochlorite&lt;/strong&gt; in commercial bleach is &lt;strong&gt;3.62%&lt;/strong&gt;. This is a carefully calculated amount to ensure effective cleaning while minimizing risks to users.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;3071&quot; data-start=&quot;2865&quot;&gt;Higher concentrations may be used in industrial applications, but for household purposes, this concentration is safe and effective.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Uses of Sodium Hypochlorite:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;3250&quot; data-start=&quot;3076&quot;&gt;It is used for &lt;strong&gt;disinfecting surfaces&lt;/strong&gt; in homes, hospitals, and laboratories.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;3402&quot; data-start=&quot;3301&quot;&gt;It is also employed in &lt;strong&gt;water treatment&lt;/strong&gt; to kill bacteria and other pathogens.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;3580&quot; data-start=&quot;3407&quot;&gt;In laundry, it acts as a &lt;strong&gt;bleaching agent&lt;/strong&gt;, removing stains and whitening clothes.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Safety Considerations:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;3729&quot; data-start=&quot;3585&quot;&gt;While effective, sodium hypochlorite must be used with caution, as it can cause irritation to the skin and eyes. Proper &lt;strong&gt;ventilation&lt;/strong&gt; and protective gear are recommended during use.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;3865&quot; data-start=&quot;3740&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Storage:&lt;/strong&gt; It should be stored in a cool, dry place away from direct sunlight to prevent decomposition.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/important-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Important Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Concentration Variations:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;4636&quot; data-start=&quot;4411&quot;&gt;Commercial bleach typically contains &lt;strong&gt;3.62%&lt;/strong&gt; sodium hypochlorite, while industrial-grade bleach may have higher concentrations, such as &lt;strong&gt;10&amp;ndash;12%&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;4761&quot; data-start=&quot;4641&quot;&gt;Diluted solutions are available for specific applications, such as sanitizing water or cleaning delicate fabrics.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Environmental Impact:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;5043&quot; data-start=&quot;4817&quot;&gt;Sodium hypochlorite can release harmful chlorine gas if mixed with acidic or ammonia-based cleaners.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;5259&quot; data-start=&quot;5048&quot;&gt;Proper disposal is necessary to prevent water pollution and harm to aquatic life.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

The correct answer is option 3,
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Angular acceleration&lt;/strong&gt; has the dimensional formula M&lt;sup&gt;0&lt;/sup&gt;L&lt;sup&gt;0&lt;/sup&gt;T&lt;sup&gt;-2&lt;/sup&gt;, indicating that it is independent of mass and length but inversely proportional to the square of time.&lt;/li&gt;
